 I want everybody to have an opportunity

00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:05.760
 to be a professional developer.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:07.120
 So I encourage you.

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:09.740
 And frankly, if you haven't taken Python yet,

00:01:09.740 --> 00:01:11.200
 like my Python for Everybody class,

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:14.760
 this course is going to be a little bit difficult.

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:17.420
 So let's start with a history of C.

00:01:17.420 --> 00:01:19.980
 The book we're looking at, The Kernigan and Ritchie,

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:25.900
 a C programming language by Brian W. Kernigan

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:30.060
 and Dennis M. Ritchie, was published in 1978.

00:01:30.060 --> 00:01:34.680
 And the key thing is that it is a moment in history

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:37.460
 where everything changed.

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:40.400
 And so we're looking at this textbook

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:42.800
 and the text in this textbook and the language itself

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:45.920
 in the context of how it has impacted history.

00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:48.960
 The C programming language itself has a long history.

00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:50.360
 There was a language called B,

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:52.440
 and they were using it at AT&T Abel Labs

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:56.160
 to build utilities and operating system stuff.

00:01:56.160 --> 00:01:59.120
 But it was a little too word-oriented.

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:02.120
 And so the language C was,

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:05.460
 as new computer hardware came out,

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:07.680
 that supported byte addressing

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:10.080
 and the ability to load a string of bytes

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:12.680
 and store a string of bytes rather than a set of words,

00:02:12.680 --> 00:02:15.220
 words being larger than a byte

00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:17.400
 and more than one character were packed into words,

00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:19.680
 and kind of like the '60s and early '70s.

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:24.120
 C wanted to make a character,

00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:29.120
 a sort of core low-level VAP kind of data

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:31.160
 that the language would happen.

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:34.120
 And from like the early and mid '70s,

00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:36.320
 the C and Unix kind of co-evolved.

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:38.680
 They wanted to build something

00:02:38.680 --> 00:02:43.260
 that would make Unix work well on a PDP 1120,

00:02:43.260 --> 00:02:45.640
 and at the same time,

00:02:45.640 --> 00:02:48.120
 make it so they could port Unix to other systems.

00:02:48.120 --> 00:02:52.200
 But really, it was about the PDP 1120's

00:02:52.200 --> 00:02:53.360
 cool memory architecture

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:55.440
 having to do with byte addressability.

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:58.360
 And what happened was is they were

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:00.800
 carefully rewriting Unix in C,

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:03.440
 but then fixing C, laying the groundwork

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:06.000
 for Unix portability.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.000
 And so by 1978, this KNRC book was published.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.880
 And at that point, you could think of it as a summary

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:18.340
 of over a decade of research in how to build

00:03:18.340 --> 00:03:20.000
 a portable programming language,

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.760
 and then use that portable programming language

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:25.600
 to build a portable operating system,

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:26.840
 C and Unix, of course.

00:03:26.840 --> 00:03:32.440
 By 1989, C had become popular,

00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:33.740
 and there was a need to standardize it.

00:03:33.740 --> 00:03:36.240
 So there's a variant of C called C89.

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:38.120
 That is the ANSI.

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:41.040
 And then that same version was called C90,

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:45.320
 is ISO, the International Organization of Standards,

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:46.480
 also standardized that.

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:49.880
 And so that was our first version of the C

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:52.280
 that we could all agree on.

00:03:52.280 --> 00:03:55.360
 The ANSI did not intend to go too far away

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:57.960
 from what we call KNRC,

00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:01.580
 but instead it just sort of nailed down a few things

00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:04.120
 that by then were important to nail down.

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:06.520
 And C has continued to evolve

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:09.800
 from sort of 1990 to the present,

00:04:09.800 --> 00:04:12.000
 and there's a number of major revisions.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.160
 But the key thing that these revisions don't do

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:16.420
 in the modern version of C

00:04:16.420 --> 00:04:18.460
 is they do not attempt to make C

00:04:18.460 --> 00:04:22.760
 easy to use language, say like Python or JavaScript.

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:27.760
 And then C knows its place in the panoply of languages

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:30.740
 and does a good job of that.

00:04:30.740 --> 00:04:35.360
 So if we look at sort of what's the future,

00:04:35.360 --> 00:04:38.720
 C is a difficult language to use

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:39.960
 as a general purpose language.

00:04:39.960 --> 00:04:42.240
 Python is a great general purpose language,

00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:45.360
 but it's not a great systems programming language.

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:47.880
 And the two things that are missing from C

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:51.540
 are the lack of really solid dynamic memory support

00:04:51.540 --> 00:04:53.480
 in the core types and libraries.

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:55.440
 And then there is no safe string type.

00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:57.800
 Strings are not, there's no string in C,

00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:00.280
 it's character arrays, and arrays have sizes.

00:05:00.280 --> 00:05:02.360
 And if you start putting stuff

00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:05.500
 beyond the boundary of that array, things just blow up.

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:11.480
 And C++ is, to me, not the sort of future version of C.

00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:14.980
 It's really a more powerful, intricate,

00:05:14.980 --> 00:05:18.000
 and flexible version of C for programmers

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.160
 who are doing really professional,

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:22.780
 intricate systems applications.

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:25.240
 Writing good C++ in some ways

00:05:25.240 --> 00:05:27.520
 is more difficult than writing good C.

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:33.600
 The languages that sort of take on C's mantle

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:35.680
 in the general purpose are things like Java,

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:38.080
 JavaScript, C#, or Python.

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:40.160
 The key thing with these languages

00:05:40.160 --> 00:05:43.880
 is they don't give you sort of strings

00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:46.080
 as just raw byte arrays.

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:49.620
 And they give us a simple object-oriented layer

00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:51.520
 that keeps us away from the metal.

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:53.560
 The goal of C is to get close to the hardware,

00:05:53.560 --> 00:05:54.960
 close to the metal.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:57.360
 And so Java, JavaScript, C#, Python

00:05:57.360 --> 00:05:58.760
 are all great languages,

00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:01.200
 and they're great for what we use them for.

00:06:01.200 --> 00:06:02.640
 They're just not well suited

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:05.160
 for writing an operating system kernel.

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:11.240
 The most likely language that is like C,

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:14.200
 like the next C, is probably Rust.

00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:17.460
 The idea of Rust is that it stays close to the metal,

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:22.320
 but then gives us some simple and safe core data types.

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:27.320
 And recently, Linux is starting to accept some Rust in Linux.

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:30.840
 And so that means that Rust has to be mature.

00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:34.460
 It means that Rust can't be evolving rapidly.

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:38.560
 I've seen situations where operating systems

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:41.360
 like macOS decide to depend on Python.

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:44.440
 So there's parts of macOS that depend on Python 2,

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:46.440
 but then they can't really upgrade to Python 2

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:48.840
 because of their operating system, blah, blah, blah.

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:51.800
 So for an operating system to depend

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:53.680
 on a programming language like Rust,

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:56.800
 it really has to be mature and,

00:06:56.800 --> 00:06:58.120
 even more importantly, stable.

00:06:58.120 --> 00:07:01.220
 You can't have clever innovations

00:07:01.220 --> 00:07:04.000
 in the programming language causing regressions

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.320
 in an operating system, say like Linux.

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:08.280
 So look for Rust.

00:07:08.280 --> 00:07:13.760
 Now, C has been around a long time.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:17.200
 Before C, we'll call C starting in '72,

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:19.140
 the book is published in '78.

00:07:19.140 --> 00:07:24.140
 Before C, most of us would write a semilanguage or Fortran.

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:28.000
 Some people wrote PL/1 that's not on here.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:31.520
 Fortran is not really a general purpose programming language.

00:07:31.520 --> 00:07:36.520
 You wouldn't write a command like cat in Fortran.

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:39.480
 Fortran was really for scientific computations.

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:42.760
 And the earliest of computers in the '50s, '60s

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:47.000
 were either sort of really specialized

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:49.680
 toward like payroll and HR systems,

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:52.600
 or they were really specialized to doing computations.

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:56.120
 And the ones that specialized were the science ones

00:07:56.120 --> 00:07:59.440
 were used Fortran 'cause it was just the right language

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:01.520
 for those computers that were aimed

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:03.960
 at doing scientific calculations.

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:07.600
 C as a language was kind of none of the above

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:12.600
 in that it was aimed at writing system code, a kernel,

00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:15.600
 an operating system, and the utilities around it,

00:08:15.600 --> 00:08:17.960
 including like other languages.

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:20.920
 And so C is kind of the mother tongue

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:24.420
 of all kinds of other derivative languages.

00:08:24.420 --> 00:08:29.180
 And things like the Bash shell, Perl, Python, PHP,

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:32.360
 C++, JavaScript, Java, and C# and Objective-C

00:08:32.360 --> 00:08:36.200
 just kind of were derivatives of this beginning of C.

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:39.200
 And that's why you see a lot of patterns

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:41.400
 in these other languages that are similar.

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:44.320
 And that's because JavaScript and Java

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:47.800
 both inherited their for loop syntax from C.

00:08:47.800 --> 00:08:51.120
 So I've got a couple of videos in this section.

00:08:51.120 --> 00:08:54.240
 This is Brian Kernigan talking about

00:08:54.240 --> 00:08:56.840
 the C programming language and it's a short video.

00:08:56.840 --> 00:08:59.720
 I didn't produce this video, but it's a great little video.

00:08:59.720 --> 00:09:04.480
 Another video is from the creator of C++, Bjorn Stroestrup.

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:05.980
 This was an interview that I did

00:09:05.980 --> 00:09:08.080
 with IEEE Computer Magazine.

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:10.200
 On top of this history of the C language,

00:09:10.200 --> 00:09:12.320
 we can look at a brief history of computers.

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:16.440
 And I have a whole course

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:18.760
 called Internet History, Technology, and Security

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:20.580
 that really starts in the 1940s

00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:24.100
 with a focus more on communication rather than computation,

00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:27.040
 even though communication and computation

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:29.760
 were very much connected throughout the 40s

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:31.180
 through even today.

00:09:31.180 --> 00:09:34.600
 In the early 1950s, computers were,

00:09:34.600 --> 00:09:35.940
 you best think of them as like

00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:38.980
 a multimillion dollar strategic asset.

00:09:38.980 --> 00:09:40.360
 Every single computer.

00:09:40.360 --> 00:09:42.280
 And a lot of them were custom built.

00:09:42.280 --> 00:09:45.280
 The first computer at Michigan State University

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:47.320
 where I went to undergrad was built

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:50.680
 by the electrical engineering students of that university

00:09:50.680 --> 00:09:52.680
 based on some designs that they borrowed, I think,

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:54.360
 from Iowa.

00:09:54.360 --> 00:09:57.160
 And so things like the programming language,

00:09:57.160 --> 00:09:58.860
 the operating system,

00:09:58.860 --> 00:10:02.200
 you didn't have a lot of generalization.

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:04.560
 You didn't have a lot of sharing.

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:07.680
 You tended to write code and put it on a paper tape,

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:10.120
 or later a magnetic tape, and load it and run it.

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:14.200
 And so you were just pretty happy if the code worked.

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:15.640
 You didn't need an operating system.

00:10:15.640 --> 00:10:17.640
 These weren't multiprocessing computers.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:21.920
 And so the software environment was very minimalist.

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:24.440
 But in the late '50s and early '60s,

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:26.180
 you saw companies like IBM

00:10:26.180 --> 00:10:28.000
 and Digital Equipment Corporation

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.320
 began selling general purpose computers.

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:31.820
 They just couldn't make them.

00:10:31.820 --> 00:10:34.080
 And they started selling them.

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:35.440
 And they still were expensive,

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:37.360
 and they were only in like,

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:39.100
 a business would have a couple of computers

00:10:39.100 --> 00:10:41.840
 to help them do payroll, perhaps, or something like that.

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:44.160
 Something that was really, really important

00:10:44.160 --> 00:10:46.040
 'cause the computers were expensive.

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:48.400
 But in the '60s,

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:50.400
 there, we really got to the point

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:53.720
 where the computer componentry, the chips, et cetera,

00:10:53.720 --> 00:10:56.000
 were becoming commodities.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
 You could just go to a place and buy chips.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:10:59.400
 And then you could make a computer

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:00.560
 by buying a bunch of chips

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:02.320
 and putting those things together.

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:05.780
 And because you weren't building everything from scratch,

00:11:05.780 --> 00:11:07.720
 the cost got a lot lower.

00:11:07.720 --> 00:11:11.000
 The other thing that these less expensive computers were

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:12.580
 is they were a little slower.

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:15.720
 But by the end of the 1960s, there was a lot of computers.

00:11:15.720 --> 00:11:20.720
 There were some super expensive, weird, one-off,

00:11:20.720 --> 00:11:23.520
 small production computers.

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:25.320
 There were computers that had,

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:28.000
 there was like the previous generation of mini-computer

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:28.960
 where there were lots of them

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:30.880
 laying around old computer science departments

00:11:30.880 --> 00:11:32.900
 or businesses that they weren't sure

00:11:32.900 --> 00:11:34.560
 what they did to do with them.

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:36.580
 They wanted to buy a new one.

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:38.640
 And then there were just innovative,

00:11:38.640 --> 00:11:41.140
 new, low-cost computers coming out.

00:11:41.140 --> 00:11:46.140
 And in the '70s, in this milieu of just lots

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:49.680
 of new and old computer hardware,

00:11:49.680 --> 00:11:53.460
 the question was is there a way we can do things

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:55.520
 with all of this old hardware?

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:57.940
 And is there sort of one solution?

00:11:57.940 --> 00:12:01.180
 And that's where Unix NC came.

00:12:01.180 --> 00:12:04.760
 And certainly after the '70s, we look at the '80s,

00:12:04.760 --> 00:12:07.200
 and that's where microprocessors and personal computers.

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:08.620
 And so we went from computers

00:12:08.620 --> 00:12:12.680
 that were sizes of refrigerators or desks

00:12:12.680 --> 00:12:15.920
 to the size of a computer could be on a single chip.

00:12:15.920 --> 00:12:18.940
 And in the beginning, those personal computers

00:12:18.940 --> 00:12:22.480
 like the IBM PC or Commodore PET,

00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:24.480
 they had really bad performance, but that performance,

00:12:24.480 --> 00:12:27.280
 once you could get everything on a single chip,

00:12:27.280 --> 00:12:29.960
 that performance could get faster very quickly.

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:33.840
 And because personal computers became a mass market item,

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:37.480
 a lot of money could be invested in personal computers.

00:12:37.480 --> 00:12:41.920
 By the 1990s, personal computers continued to grow, right?

00:12:41.920 --> 00:12:45.820
 And, but the need to communicate and talk

00:12:45.820 --> 00:12:48.240
 and exchange information became important.

00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:51.440
 And so in the 1990s, we saw really an increasing focus

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:54.040
 on connecting computers with the internet

00:12:54.040 --> 00:12:55.440
 and other kinds of networks.

00:12:55.440 --> 00:12:57.160
 And the performance of these computers

00:12:57.160 --> 00:13:00.640
 and the price kept going down, the performance kept going up.

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:03.120
 And then by the time we get to the 2000s,

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:06.520
 Amazon's AWS was founded in 2002,

00:13:06.520 --> 00:13:09.400
 and it used personal computer microprocessors

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:13.640
 like from Intel and produced computing as a commodity, right?

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:16.120
 And so, and you don't even buy computers anymore.

00:13:16.120 --> 00:13:17.320
 You just go to Amazon and say,

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:20.440
 I'll rent a computer for $7 a month.

00:13:20.440 --> 00:13:25.440
 And so we see in 1978, we see this moment

00:13:25.440 --> 00:13:30.860
 where the computers were becoming more common,

00:13:30.860 --> 00:13:32.400
 they're going down in price,

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:33.840
 and there's getting to be more and more of them.

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:36.080
 And there was a diversity of computers.

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:38.480
 These days, there's actually less diversity.

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:41.680
 If we go back in history,

00:13:41.680 --> 00:13:43.680
 and you take a look at my internet history class,

00:13:43.680 --> 00:13:45.680
 you can see the, I go to Bletchley Park

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:48.440
 and show you some of the earliest computations

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:50.940
 from the 1940s and World War II.

00:13:50.940 --> 00:13:55.380
 We go to Computer History Museum in California

00:13:55.380 --> 00:13:59.340
 and visit with Gordon Bell and talk about the PDP-1.

00:13:59.340 --> 00:14:02.960
 And he talks a lot about buying the components

00:14:02.960 --> 00:14:04.260
 and putting the components together

00:14:04.260 --> 00:14:07.220
 and how sort of the mass availability

00:14:07.220 --> 00:14:10.800
 of relatively low-cost components really allowed

00:14:10.800 --> 00:14:13.420
 for a rapid innovation in computer architecture.

00:14:13.420 --> 00:14:17.720
 A computer that I used in my computer science degree

00:14:17.720 --> 00:14:20.320
 was the Control Data CDC 6500.

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:22.380
 And I have a video where we visit

00:14:22.380 --> 00:14:25.160
 the Living Computer Museum in Seattle, Washington,

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:29.040
 and hear card readers work and card punches.

00:14:29.040 --> 00:14:31.160
 And if we ever get to the point

00:14:31.160 --> 00:14:32.440
 where everything opens back up again,

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:36.680
 it's a tremendous visit to go see all the technology

00:14:36.680 --> 00:14:38.240
 that really through the years,

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:40.720
 except that in the Living Computer Museum,

00:14:40.720 --> 00:14:42.640
 they like to have everything running.

00:14:42.640 --> 00:14:44.840
 And then you can take a look at a more modern,

00:14:44.840 --> 00:14:46.280
 smaller Raspberry Pi,

00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:49.540
 which the Raspberry Pi is actually not an Intel-based system.

00:14:49.540 --> 00:14:53.160
 The Raspberry Pi is based on ARM,

00:14:53.160 --> 00:14:55.800
 the processor that really became popular

00:14:55.800 --> 00:14:58.000
 as a result of the cell phone revolution.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.800
 And so the Raspberry Pi is to take

00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:03.680
 what the technology was advanced,

00:15:03.680 --> 00:15:07.900
 both low-power and high-performance technology

00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:11.200
 that was advanced because of mobile phone innovations.

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:12.720
 The Raspberry Pi came out

00:15:12.720 --> 00:15:14.680
 and was a good single-board computer.

00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:16.160
 So let's take a look at the operating system.

00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:20.200
 Unix is the operating system that is connected with C.

00:15:20.200 --> 00:15:23.120
 In the 1960s, there was a multi-user operating system

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:24.240
 called Multics.

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:27.720
 And then in the 1970s,

00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:30.520
 they wanted to come up with yet another operating system,

00:15:30.520 --> 00:15:32.560
 and they eventually called it Unix,

00:15:32.560 --> 00:15:34.560
 and the DEC PDP1120,

00:15:34.560 --> 00:15:39.560
 which was one of these new commodity part-based computers

00:15:39.560 --> 00:15:44.000
 that was coming into the marketplace.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.580
 And so in 1973, Unix was rewritten in C,

00:15:47.580 --> 00:15:50.120
 but it only was there on the PDP11,

00:15:50.120 --> 00:15:54.720
 although they had laid the groundwork for portability

00:15:54.720 --> 00:15:55.920
 from the beginning.

00:15:55.920 --> 00:16:00.200
 They knew they wanted to have everything be portable.

00:16:00.200 --> 00:16:02.360
 They just couldn't make it all portable.

00:16:02.360 --> 00:16:03.680
 The first version,

00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:05.560
 they just had to make it run on the PDP11.

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:07.920
 And then by 1978, the Unix,

00:16:07.920 --> 00:16:10.420
 the second computer that Unix had run on

00:16:10.420 --> 00:16:12.040
 was an Interdata 832,

00:16:12.040 --> 00:16:14.000
 and that was quite a different computer.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:14.840
 And so it was good.

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:17.400
 And so they really learned a lot about making Unix

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:19.160
 a portable bit of software.

00:16:19.160 --> 00:16:24.080
 In the early 1970s, C was evolving in a way

00:16:24.080 --> 00:16:26.480
 so that the Unix could be ported, right?

00:16:26.480 --> 00:16:28.000
 So it's like, let's,

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.340
 we got this problem between, let's just say,

00:16:30.340 --> 00:16:32.760
 the PDP11 and the Interdata.

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:34.780
 And how can we fix this?

00:16:34.780 --> 00:16:37.540
 And we can both change how the operating system works.

00:16:37.540 --> 00:16:39.480
 We can change the operating system code,

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:41.320
 and we can change the C compiler,

00:16:41.320 --> 00:16:44.160
 and then we can rewrite the operating system code

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:46.660
 to get less and less assembly language

00:16:46.660 --> 00:16:48.000
 and more and more C language.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
 And so the idea was to get to the point

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.040
 where there was a very, very small amount

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:55.380
 of assembly language in Unix.

00:16:55.380 --> 00:16:57.840
 And over the years, that's gotten lower and lower.

00:16:57.840 --> 00:17:00.720
 Unix was rewritten.

00:17:00.720 --> 00:17:02.960
 A number of versions came out in the '70s,

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:05.120
 having to do with their portability.

00:17:05.120 --> 00:17:08.640
 So by 1978, the Unix version 7 could also run

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:12.000
 on a whole new architecture from DEC called the VAX systems.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.120
 University of California, Berkeley

00:17:15.120 --> 00:17:19.320
 had their own distribution of Unix called BSD,

00:17:19.320 --> 00:17:21.200
 the Berkeley Software Distribution.

00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:22.640
 And that was really cool

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:26.600
 because universities often pushed things like networking,

00:17:26.600 --> 00:17:28.480
 TCP/IP, ARPANET.

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:33.500
 BSD Unix was the first place some of us saw TCP/IP.

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:37.800
 1982, a company based solely on Unix

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:40.280
 called Sun Microsystems was found.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:43.320
 Sun was some work at Stanford, some work at Berkeley,

00:17:43.320 --> 00:17:45.360
 all based on Unix, and they created

00:17:45.360 --> 00:17:48.060
 what in effect was the Unix Workstation Marketplace.

00:17:48.060 --> 00:17:51.640
 At this point, you could imagine that the world was about

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:54.360
 to just adopt Unix.

00:17:54.360 --> 00:17:56.340
 Unix was the greatest thing ever.

00:17:56.340 --> 00:18:00.840
 Computer science departments were teaching Unix

00:18:00.840 --> 00:18:05.140
 in their operating systems classes in the mid '80s.

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:08.720
 The problem became AT&T had never come up really

00:18:08.720 --> 00:18:12.360
 with a business plan for what the purpose of Unix was,

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:15.600
 and so there was some fits and starts

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:20.440
 as to how they could monetize this extremely popular thing.

00:18:20.440 --> 00:18:25.020
 And they didn't do a great job,

00:18:25.020 --> 00:18:27.440
 and it took them a long time to figure out

00:18:27.440 --> 00:18:29.840
 what was going to be successful.

00:18:29.840 --> 00:18:34.980
 And by the time AT&T sort of figured things out,

00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:40.160
 the market had moved on.

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:43.680
 And so Minix is an operating system

00:18:43.680 --> 00:18:46.680
 that was developed in the Netherlands by Andrew Tannenbaum,

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:48.920
 and he built a completely free

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:50.840
 and open source operating system

00:18:50.840 --> 00:18:52.720
 that was used for education.

00:18:52.720 --> 00:18:56.480
 He built a textbook around it, and it was very popular.

00:18:56.480 --> 00:19:00.280
 But he didn't want commercialization,

00:19:00.280 --> 00:19:01.720
 at least not at that point in time,

00:19:01.720 --> 00:19:05.200
 so he sort of held onto it too tightly.

00:19:05.200 --> 00:19:08.200
 Again, kind of an intellectual property mistake.

00:19:08.200 --> 00:19:12.960
 And in 1991, a program called Linus Torvalds decided

00:19:12.960 --> 00:19:15.960
 he was going to build a fresh ground-up implementation

00:19:15.960 --> 00:19:19.040
 of the Unix kernel that was 100% free.

00:19:19.040 --> 00:19:20.560
 So he wasn't going to use Unix.

00:19:20.560 --> 00:19:21.800
 He wasn't going to use Minix.

00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:23.600
 He wanted to create another thing.

00:19:23.600 --> 00:19:25.480
 And originally, it was just like a hobby.

00:19:25.480 --> 00:19:27.600
 I'm going to try to see how far I can go.

00:19:27.600 --> 00:19:30.160
 By 1992, Linux started to work,

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:32.840
 and it adopted this license called the GPL,

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:35.280
 which is called the GNU Public Library License,

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:38.440
 which is a strongly open source license

00:19:38.440 --> 00:19:40.040
 in the way that it's difficult

00:19:40.040 --> 00:19:43.280
 to take Linux out of open source,

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:47.160
 which meant that people could then invest in Linux.

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:51.320
 And so Linux has become Unix, right?

00:19:51.320 --> 00:19:55.040
 Linux in the modern world is the Unix-like system.

00:19:55.040 --> 00:19:57.400
 And Unix tried to hold on for a while,

00:19:57.400 --> 00:19:59.080
 but they really, really couldn't.

00:19:59.080 --> 00:20:02.800
 And so the remaining Unix distributions

00:20:02.800 --> 00:20:07.040
 are a tiny, tiny fraction of the marketplace,

00:20:07.040 --> 00:20:10.120
 and Linux is the marketplace.

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:12.040
 So we can see some of this in some of the videos

00:20:12.040 --> 00:20:14.040
 that I've got, like Andrew Tannenbaum

00:20:14.040 --> 00:20:16.640
 will tell us the story of how Minix was created

00:20:16.640 --> 00:20:19.440
 and how Minix kind of begat Linux,

00:20:19.440 --> 00:20:22.200
 and so that there's some interesting stuff here, okay?

00:20:22.200 --> 00:20:25.200
 So I'll lay on top of all this.

00:20:25.200 --> 00:20:27.800
 Remember that 1978 is this moment in history

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:29.680
 where I claim like everything changed.

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:32.840
 Now I've been a computer scientist for a very long time.

00:20:32.840 --> 00:20:35.680
 I started in 1975.

00:20:35.680 --> 00:20:40.600
 And in 1975, I learned things like Fortran on a computer,

00:20:40.600 --> 00:20:42.800
 that CDC 6500 computer.

00:20:42.800 --> 00:20:45.840
 It ran a special operating system called Scope Hustler.

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:48.680
 I knew how to do assembly, I knew Fortran,

00:20:48.680 --> 00:20:50.080
 and even Pascal.

00:20:50.080 --> 00:20:55.160
 So Pascal in the '70s was one of these languages that,

00:20:55.160 --> 00:20:57.400
 and I've got a video for Pascal as well,

00:20:57.400 --> 00:20:59.200
 one of these languages that was sort of like saying,

00:20:59.200 --> 00:21:01.640
 "Look, here's the future."

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:03.760
 Now Pascal was really aimed at teaching,

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:06.520
 and so I used Pascal in educational context.

00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:10.680
 And as I became a professional programmer in the 1980s,

00:21:10.680 --> 00:21:12.560
 I was using a bunch of stuff.

00:21:12.560 --> 00:21:16.360
 Assembly language, COBOL, a little bit of Unix and C here.

00:21:16.360 --> 00:21:19.840
 It wasn't like by the early '80s, Unix was everywhere,

00:21:19.840 --> 00:21:21.440
 at least not in the professional world,

00:21:21.440 --> 00:21:23.680
 because the PC revolution was happening.

00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:26.320
 So we had DOS, we had early Windows versions.

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:29.560
 I used things like DBase and Turbo Pascal.

00:21:29.560 --> 00:21:32.880
 I taught classes of the IBM 360,

00:21:32.880 --> 00:21:34.680
 and I taught assembly language.

00:21:34.680 --> 00:21:37.760
 I used the DECVAX, and I used the VMS, not Unix operating

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:39.280
 system and Fortran.

00:21:39.280 --> 00:21:43.480
 And I also then taught in the mid '80s on an AT&T Western,

00:21:43.480 --> 00:21:47.120
 I think it's called, a GE AT&T 3B2.

00:21:47.120 --> 00:21:49.520
 I taught Unix, I taught C, and I taught Fortran.

00:21:49.520 --> 00:21:54.200
 And so even though we can trace back to like 1978

00:21:54.200 --> 00:21:56.160
 is the moment that everything changed,

00:21:56.160 --> 00:21:58.920
 it's not like the market changed.

00:21:58.920 --> 00:22:02.520
 The thing that happened in the 1990s though,

00:22:02.520 --> 00:22:06.320
 is that all these older computers and the older computers,

00:22:06.320 --> 00:22:11.320
 vendors like Burrows and Unisys and IBM and Cray

00:22:11.320 --> 00:22:17.480
 and Control Data, as microprocessor speeds increased,

00:22:17.480 --> 00:22:21.160
 all these little companies would create Unix workstations

00:22:21.160 --> 00:22:24.040
 that were faster and faster and faster.

00:22:24.040 --> 00:22:27.480
 And because they could build new hardware that was fast

00:22:27.480 --> 00:22:29.920
 and then grab the Unix operating system

00:22:31.760 --> 00:22:35.120
 and make their operating system work on their new hardware,

00:22:35.120 --> 00:22:37.680
 it allowed for some amazing innovation.

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:41.520
 So I was using Sun, Ardent, Stellar, these are all gone now.

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:46.240
 IBM RS6000, Convex C2400, I had a Next on my desk,

00:22:46.240 --> 00:22:51.240
 I use C, but TCP/IP, Windows, HTTP, the web, you know,

00:22:51.240 --> 00:22:56.320
 and Windows and Mac OS were all kind of in the mix.

00:22:56.320 --> 00:22:59.280
 But the innovation was really happening most rapidly

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:00.840
 in the Unix space.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:05.600
 But by the 2000s, everything that I touched

00:23:05.600 --> 00:23:08.320
 really had some aspect, I'm not a Windows person,

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:11.640
 so everything I touched had some aspect of Unix in it.

00:23:11.640 --> 00:23:15.440
 Mac OS still has Unix in it, Linux and my languages

00:23:15.440 --> 00:23:20.440
 are sort of narrowing back down to Java, PHP and JavaScript.

00:23:20.440 --> 00:23:24.200
 And then in 2010s, right?

00:23:24.200 --> 00:23:27.560
 Linux, Mac OS, Python, PHP, JavaScript.

00:23:27.560 --> 00:23:31.640
 So things really have settled into a world

00:23:31.640 --> 00:23:33.680
 that my own software development,

00:23:33.680 --> 00:23:38.040
 where I'm pretty much using Unix-like systems all the time

00:23:38.040 --> 00:23:41.720
 and C-based or C-derived languages,

00:23:41.720 --> 00:23:45.680
 'cause Python, Java, PHP and JavaScript are all based on C.

00:23:45.680 --> 00:23:49.080
 And that's why it's so important to understand C.

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:52.880
 I'm not writing C as a professional in any way,

00:23:52.880 --> 00:23:56.160
 but I am using all my C knowledge every single day.

00:23:56.160 --> 00:24:00.520
 And so that's sort of a picture of me in my office,

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:03.840
 that's an IBM PS/2 in my office.

00:24:03.840 --> 00:24:06.760
 I was registering in 1989,

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:09.000
 I was registering with punch cards.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:11.200
 When I first started, I was using a line printer

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:14.480
 and punch cards and so there's my history.

00:24:14.480 --> 00:24:18.040
 Now, I think it's important to acknowledge

00:24:18.040 --> 00:24:21.560
 that as I've shown you all these history documents

00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:24.000
 and the videos and the oral histories that I've done,

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:29.000
 is there is a preponderance of old white males in here.

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:35.080
 And I think that it is important to talk a bit about that

00:24:35.080 --> 00:24:37.280
 and why that is perhaps.

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:42.280
 And so I would encourage you to take a look at an article,

00:24:42.280 --> 00:24:46.280
 so NPR article, it's actually, you can listen to it,

00:24:46.280 --> 00:24:48.080
 about what happened to computer science.

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:50.560
 The title of the article is "When Women Stop Coding."

00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:51.760
 All the way up to 1980,

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:54.560
 computer science was just another field.

00:24:54.560 --> 00:24:58.280
 And then it kept going up to sort of 1985,

00:24:58.280 --> 00:25:02.200
 but then it went down and so all these other fields

00:25:02.200 --> 00:25:04.440
 have a pretty good gender mix

00:25:04.440 --> 00:25:07.640
 and the computer science does not have a gender mix.

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:11.600
 And so I would encourage you to listen to this article.

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:16.520
 Another area that you can learn something about,

00:25:16.520 --> 00:25:19.600
 the diversity in computer science is this book

00:25:19.600 --> 00:25:23.080
 by Jane Margolis called "Unlocking the Clubhouse."

00:25:23.080 --> 00:25:24.960
 The essence of the book is really talking

00:25:24.960 --> 00:25:29.800
 about how social pressure, advertising pressure

00:25:29.800 --> 00:25:32.600
 in the early '80s made it seem

00:25:32.600 --> 00:25:35.920
 as though computing was a guy thing.

00:25:35.920 --> 00:25:40.440
 And in particular, it made it so that young men,

00:25:40.440 --> 00:25:41.320
 even in high school,

00:25:41.320 --> 00:25:43.840
 would go fiddle around with computers as a hobby.

00:25:43.840 --> 00:25:46.400
 And by the time they got to college, they were pretty skilled.

00:25:46.400 --> 00:25:51.320
 And if you weren't skilled, the college classes were designed

00:25:51.320 --> 00:25:53.440
 for people who already knew what programming was.

00:25:53.440 --> 00:25:56.800
 And if you were a woman and you hadn't played with computers

00:25:56.800 --> 00:26:00.720
 in 1980, when you were like 14 years old,

00:26:00.720 --> 00:26:02.920
 you came to college at a distinct disadvantage.

00:26:02.920 --> 00:26:05.880
 And this is what led to this fall off

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:09.000
 where colleges tended to teach to programmers

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:10.720
 who already knew how to program.

00:26:10.720 --> 00:26:14.480
 And that really meant that the hobbyists,

00:26:14.480 --> 00:26:17.240
 people who were in their youth before they went to college

00:26:17.240 --> 00:26:19.640
 and played with programming as a hobby

00:26:19.640 --> 00:26:21.160
 had a tremendous advantage.

00:26:22.160 --> 00:26:27.160
 Now, Jane did her work in the '80s, late '80s and '90s.

00:26:27.160 --> 00:26:30.320
 I myself am older than that.

00:26:30.320 --> 00:26:33.040
 And I think that to some degree,

00:26:33.040 --> 00:26:35.440
 this notion of the social pressure

00:26:35.440 --> 00:26:41.120
 that said that computing was really for young men

00:26:41.120 --> 00:26:45.640
 and not young woman, it's actually as much a symptom

00:26:45.640 --> 00:26:46.880
 as it is the cause.

00:26:46.880 --> 00:26:50.080
 Because I grew up in a time in the mid '70s

00:26:50.080 --> 00:26:52.680
 where there were women everywhere.

00:26:52.680 --> 00:26:57.360
 And this is a person who had a really large impact

00:26:57.360 --> 00:26:59.560
 in my life, her name is Helen Spence.

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:01.760
 She was a professor at Michigan State University

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:04.640
 and I show you a URL to look at her oral history.

00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:08.520
 She taught me operating systems.

00:27:08.520 --> 00:27:12.480
 So in 1977 or 1978, I don't remember when,

00:27:12.480 --> 00:27:15.120
 Helen was my operating systems teacher.

00:27:15.120 --> 00:27:17.080
 The interesting thing about how Helen taught

00:27:17.080 --> 00:27:20.960
 operating systems was she made it fun.

00:27:20.960 --> 00:27:23.440
 It was really fun.

00:27:23.440 --> 00:27:26.680
 I encountered my first auto grader in Helen's class.

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:29.040
 She had made a piece of software

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:31.680
 that she called the HMS 5050,

00:27:31.680 --> 00:27:35.000
 which itself is both Helen Spence

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:38.240
 and I think it's Her Majesty's ship at the same time.

00:27:38.240 --> 00:27:41.480
 And what she did was she built a operating system simulator

00:27:41.480 --> 00:27:45.360
 in Fortran and our job as taking the class

00:27:45.360 --> 00:27:49.600
 was to build functions and subroutines

00:27:49.600 --> 00:27:52.160
 that would implement the tasks and the algorithms

00:27:52.160 --> 00:27:53.920
 that operating systems need to do.

00:27:53.920 --> 00:27:57.280
 So you'd run your program over and over and over again

00:27:57.280 --> 00:27:59.960
 until you had written a successful operating system

00:27:59.960 --> 00:28:03.360
 and she wrote a auto grader that would do things

00:28:03.360 --> 00:28:06.400
 to your program and then measure whether or not

00:28:06.400 --> 00:28:08.960
 you knew how to build an operating system.

00:28:08.960 --> 00:28:12.480
 It was just a natural thing to have females

00:28:12.480 --> 00:28:16.800
 as faculty members and there was a lot more fun

00:28:16.800 --> 00:28:20.880
 in the field and I have my own theories

00:28:20.880 --> 00:28:24.360
 that I think compliment Jane's theories as well

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:27.840
 but I'll leave it here that that's a TED talk

00:28:27.840 --> 00:28:31.320
 for another day as to gender and computing.

00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:33.240
 Right now I'm just acknowledging it

00:28:33.240 --> 00:28:37.080
 and giving you some resources to read

00:28:37.080 --> 00:28:39.160
 and reach your own conclusions.

00:28:39.160 --> 00:28:42.400
 If you look at everything I've done since 2012

00:28:42.400 --> 00:28:45.680
 in the free online education in MOOC space,

00:28:45.680 --> 00:28:48.000
 you'll notice that every course I've ever created

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.880
 has the words for everybody

00:28:49.880 --> 00:28:52.080
 and that's not just a marketing thing,

00:28:52.080 --> 00:28:53.960
 that's because it's my philosophy.

00:28:53.960 --> 00:28:55.800
 If you've taken some of my classes like Python

00:28:55.800 --> 00:28:57.280
 for everybody or Django for everybody,

00:28:57.280 --> 00:28:59.600
 web applications for everybody, Postgres for everybody

00:28:59.600 --> 00:29:01.720
 and now C programming for everybody,

00:29:01.720 --> 00:29:05.640
 I try to build a course where I spend time

00:29:05.640 --> 00:29:09.240
 thinking about how not to create the clubhouse

00:29:09.240 --> 00:29:14.000
 that Jane talks about and that is I want you in the club,

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:15.720
 I want everybody in the club,

00:29:15.720 --> 00:29:19.480
 I don't want it just to be a club for the super geniuses

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:23.320
 and so part of why I'm building an entire curriculum

00:29:23.320 --> 00:29:27.720
 is to perhaps just make a new club

00:29:27.720 --> 00:29:30.280
 and that is programming for everybody club

00:29:30.280 --> 00:29:33.240
 and I think once you become a great programmer,

00:29:33.240 --> 00:29:35.760
 I think that's a good time to study computer science

00:29:35.760 --> 00:29:38.880
 and so perhaps after we teach everybody programming,

00:29:38.880 --> 00:29:40.760
 then we can teach everybody computer science

00:29:40.760 --> 00:29:44.080
 but again, that's a TED talk for another day.

00:29:44.080 --> 00:29:48.080
 So on to the course, C programming for everybody.

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:50.360
 I'll just say that C is the most important

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:53.440
 programming language you're going to ever learn.

00:29:53.440 --> 00:29:55.400
 It should never be the first programming language

00:29:55.400 --> 00:29:56.720
 taught to any students.

00:29:56.720 --> 00:30:01.040
 You will likely never write a line of C

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:04.320
 in a professional context in your career.

00:30:04.320 --> 00:30:06.920
 I'm not teaching you C so that you can go

00:30:06.920 --> 00:30:09.080
 be a professional C programmer.

00:30:09.080 --> 00:30:10.240
 I'm teaching you C so you can be

00:30:10.240 --> 00:30:12.120
 a professional Java programmer really

00:30:12.120 --> 00:30:14.880
 but if you learn C at the right time

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:16.920
 in your learning journey,

00:30:16.920 --> 00:30:18.960
 it's a necessary step on the path

00:30:18.960 --> 00:30:20.760
 to becoming a master programmer

00:30:20.760 --> 00:30:22.560
 but it's an important step

00:30:22.560 --> 00:30:24.760
 'cause I can't teach you Java

00:30:24.760 --> 00:30:26.720
 if I hadn't already taught you C.

00:30:26.720 --> 00:30:31.320
 I have to explain how Java works

00:30:31.320 --> 00:30:35.040
 in terms of what you're going to learn in this class.

00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:38.040
 So this class is not just like get a C certificate

00:30:38.040 --> 00:30:39.840
 and go make lots of money

00:30:39.840 --> 00:30:42.080
 'cause I don't think that this certificate's

00:30:42.080 --> 00:30:43.960
 going to make you a lot of money

00:30:43.960 --> 00:30:46.280
 but I do think this certificate is going to unlock

00:30:46.280 --> 00:30:48.360
 the future of you as a programmer.

00:30:48.360 --> 00:30:54.240
 So please be patient with this material.

00:30:54.240 --> 00:30:56.160
 Do not rush.

00:30:56.160 --> 00:30:57.920
 It's an online class.

00:30:57.920 --> 00:30:59.960
 I guarantee that you can search for solutions

00:30:59.960 --> 00:31:02.560
 to every programming exercise that I create.

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:04.360
 I don't change them that much

00:31:04.360 --> 00:31:06.120
 so the solutions are out there

00:31:06.120 --> 00:31:08.000
 and if your goal is to game it

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:09.920
 and just search for solutions to programming,

00:31:09.920 --> 00:31:11.400
 go ahead, finish the class.

00:31:11.400 --> 00:31:13.080
 Congratulations.

00:31:13.080 --> 00:31:16.680
 But you have just taken the opportunity

00:31:16.680 --> 00:31:19.160
 to learn from yourself, right?

00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:20.680
 You didn't trick me.

00:31:20.680 --> 00:31:24.800
 I didn't lose anything by you searching for

00:31:24.800 --> 00:31:27.600
 and just pasting in solutions to programs.

00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:31.240
 Each exercise from beginning to end

00:31:31.240 --> 00:31:34.760
 is trying to take you a little tiny step further

00:31:34.760 --> 00:31:36.960
 down your understanding.

00:31:36.960 --> 00:31:38.760
 And the easy exercises in the beginning,

00:31:38.760 --> 00:31:40.240
 even if I have a bunch of them,

00:31:40.240 --> 00:31:42.880
 they're there to prepare and strengthen you

00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:45.240
 for something much more challenging in the course.

00:31:45.240 --> 00:31:47.720
 If you start pasting in solutions

00:31:47.720 --> 00:31:49.320
 in the beginning of the course,

00:31:49.320 --> 00:31:52.800
 you have no chance in the end of the course

00:31:52.800 --> 00:31:54.920
 and you're just gonna be pasting in solutions

00:31:54.920 --> 00:31:58.880
 and when you do that, you'll have only wasted your time.

00:32:00.040 --> 00:32:05.040
 So, I look forward to you taking the rest of this course.

00:32:05.040 --> 00:32:08.720
 Of course, I look forward to you telling me

00:32:08.720 --> 00:32:11.120
 if I'm right in my instinct

00:32:11.120 --> 00:32:13.520
 about how important this is for you,

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:15.880
 especially after you take a few more classes

00:32:15.880 --> 00:32:20.240
 and then find your way to being a professional.

